<div id="review_1945606704" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1945606704" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3143117-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571421692p2/3143117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1945606704?book_show_action=true">Mar 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/3143117-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789707705210" href="/book/show/139022.La_guerra_del_fin_del_mundo">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=espa%C3%B1ol">español</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=latin-american-lit">latin-american-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=peruano">peruano</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1945606704" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer197574432441823230">¡Alabado sea el Buen Jesús! <br/><br/>I made it. I will not lie, I had a war with this book. <br/><br/>It was good. !Verdad! It was hard to read at times. !Muy verdad! 920 páginas en español! Not only one of the biggest books I have ever read, but in Spanish. It is by Mario Vargas Llosa, one of my favourite authors. The language skills are excelente, the characters buenos y malos, and the plot flows como el río.<br/><br/>¡Alabado sea paz.<br/><br/>Pero está guerra. A war. And it was very graphic and hard to take. Countless hordes of d</span>
  <span id="freeText197574432441823230" style="display:none">¡Alabado sea el Buen Jesús! <br /><br />I made it. I will not lie, I had a war with this book. <br /><br />It was good. !Verdad! It was hard to read at times. !Muy verdad! 920 páginas en español! Not only one of the biggest books I have ever read, but in Spanish. It is by Mario Vargas Llosa, one of my favourite authors. The language skills are excelente, the characters buenos y malos, and the plot flows como el río.<br /><br />¡Alabado sea paz.<br /><br />Pero está guerra. A war. And it was very graphic and hard to take. Countless hordes of dead, maimed and the mentally ruined. Best not to dwell here.<br /><br />¡Alabado sea la verdad!<br /><br />This is the retelling of the war of the Canudos in the Salvador-Bahía area of Brazil.<br />Around the late 1870s a messianic-like figure, Antonio Counselheiro (The Counsellor) preaches the second-coming, attracting a following of disciples and stirs up a rejection of the Brazilian state: no civil marriages, abandoning using the state currency and horrors, rejects the metric system. His followers are ultra-religious and want to be left alone (or die and go to paradise). Although Brazil has become a republic, there is talk of bringing back the monarchy through a group called the Sebastian's. Trouble is brewing with a mysterious Scottish character Galileo Gall who has designs on revolution. Enter a small military troop of thirty to quash the rebellion, only to have them all slaughtered. Send in a war hero and more troops to start a civil war. And let the bloodshed flow. And does it ever.<br /><br />¡Alabado sea los caracteres!<br /><br />Perhaps handled by any other author, one might have had a different story. But with Vargas Llosa, the characters are truly amazing, heroic, sad, pathetic or show promise. The Barón Cañabrava is a wicked character, sleeping with his maid and hints at returning the monarchy while Galileo Gall, at first seems like the good guy, but turns out to being used. What I found intriguing were the back stories of the disciples around The Counsellor. One begins to see why this rag tag group felt connected. <br /><br />But the trio that become the main characters are fantastic. The myopic journalist resells the story to the Baron while trying to find out if the baron colluded with the rebels. Jurema is stolen from her husband by the plotting Gall and ends up in the midst of all the violence and meets the bearded Dwarf. The dwarf was part of a traveling circus that sadly got caught up in the war and she turns out to be one of the pillars of strength. The whole host of characters, some who just turn up and disappear, make this book move along. <br /><br />¡Alabado sea el fin!<br /><br />But this book was long. I cannot lie. Perhaps that was Vargas Llosa's message? Any war involves a host of people, who take sides or become victims. When any war ends, one asks that question, "was it worth it"? Was it worth reading it? Yes, but at times it was like a war that seemed to never end and times I thoroughly enjoyed the moments, whether good or bad. It is a monument to peace because war really has no answers other than death for so many.<br /><br />Highly recommend it but be forewarned.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="197574432441823230" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


