  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_127240532" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/127240532" />
    <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly"><img alt="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349701607p2/2190636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/127240532?book_show_action=true">Oct 21, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly">Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer127240532" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3433425797308316958">The two most prolific killers the world has ever known. No, not Hitler and Stalin. I refer to the twin scourge of mankind: RELIGION and POLITICS.<br/><br/>The RELIGION: a very charismatic, itinerant preacher named the Counselor managed to establish a large following among the poor, the unfortunate, the abnormal and the rejects of society in the 19th century Mexico. He mouths the name of Jesus Christ and preaches the message of hope, forgiveness and salvation for those who believe. They look at the governm</span>
  <span id="freeText3433425797308316958" style="display:none">The two most prolific killers the world has ever known. No, not Hitler and Stalin. I refer to the twin scourge of mankind: RELIGION and POLITICS.<br /><br />The RELIGION: a very charismatic, itinerant preacher named the Counselor managed to establish a large following among the poor, the unfortunate, the abnormal and the rejects of society in the 19th century Mexico. He mouths the name of Jesus Christ and preaches the message of hope, forgiveness and salvation for those who believe. They look at the government (the Republic) as the Anti-Christ because it has laws which they find contrary to their beliefs (among which laws, the legalization of civil weddings and taxation). He and his followers put up a "city" (more like a commune) in a jungle but which land is owned by a rich landlord. There they live in peace but without recognizing the national government and ignoring its laws. To his followers, the Counselor is someone sent by God ("Blessed be Jesus the Counselor!") as he performs miraculous conversions of men: the most hardened criminals repent of their ways, the downtrodden get comfort, hope is received by those who knew nothing but scorn, fear, hatred, hunger and crimes all their lives.<br /><br />The POLITICS: apparently, the Mexican Republic was still new then. Before, the system of government was monarchial. The Republicans still eye the Monarchists with suspicion. Indeed, as in all groups ousted from power, there was reason to believe that the latter may be planning a comeback.<br /><br />Initially I thought that this was pure fiction (although I was already wondering, at the outset, why Mario Vargas Llosa--a Peruvian--would place the setting of his work not in Peru but in Mexico). Llosa, however, won the most recent Nobel prize for literature (long overdue, many say, except that Llosa--who once ran and lost the Peruvian presidential race--has had bad politics) and midway through this book I read in a newspaper article about him that this novel was based on a true historical event. There was really that place called Canudos where the Counselor and his followers established their own city.<br /><br />The men of the Republic looked at Canudos and the Counselor with alarm. They suspected that they are being supported, secretly, by the Monarchists--the enemies of the Republic out to restore the Empire.<br /><br />Inside this explosive brew of religion and politics Llosa weaves his stories, going from one character to another, not only within Canudos, but within the quarters of the Monarchists and Republicans as well. He TAKES you inside the pages of the book, clamps the book down, and prevents your escape from his merciless story-telling.<br /><br />This morning, I was driving at around 7:00 a.m. and was blinded by the rising sun. I squinted at that orange orb rising from the horizon and I thought: this was the same hot sun which gave the Counselor's fighters--armed only with arrows, machetes, knives and a few guns stolen from the Republic's army--difficulties during the fourth and final assault of Canudos which finally brought them down. Estimated casualties: between 25,000 to 30,000 men, women and children dead. Only 7 from Canudos were captured alive. The Republic's army lost 823 men.<br /><br />Has this been made into a movie?</span>
  <a data-text-id="3433425797308316958" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review127240532">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
        <a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link127240532" title="Flag this review as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=127240532&amp;resource_type=Review&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F53925.The_War_of_the_End_of_the_World">flag</a>





