<div id="review_2665503111" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2665503111" />
    <a title="SAM" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57392386-sam"><img alt="SAM" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556638019p2/57392386.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2665503111?book_show_action=true">Jan 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="SAM" class="user" itemprop="url" name="SAM" href="/user/show/57392386-sam">SAM</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57392386-sam?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57392386-sam?shelf=historical-fiction-etc">historical-fiction-etc</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2665503111" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16629884823280628961">My second outing with the brilliant Mario Vargas Llosa and it’s been another lesson in the dark side of history. I started with <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2576742279?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Feast of the Goat</a> , which documented the last days of Rafael Trujillo and now I have worked my way through the extremely dense The War of the End of the World, which felt like 800 pages instead of the 568 pages it actually was. <br/><br/>This time the recounting was of The War of Canudos, which took place in late 1800’s Brazil, a subject I would rather have learned about duri</span>
  <span id="freeText16629884823280628961" style="display:none">My second outing with the brilliant Mario Vargas Llosa and it’s been another lesson in the dark side of history. I started with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2576742279?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">The Feast of the Goat</a> , which documented the last days of Rafael Trujillo and now I have worked my way through the extremely dense The War of the End of the World, which felt like 800 pages instead of the 568 pages it actually was. <br /><br />This time the recounting was of The War of Canudos, which took place in late 1800’s Brazil, a subject I would rather have learned about during GCSE History than the mundane nonsense my head was filled with. For the uninitiated Canudos was a piece of territory in Brazil that was claimed by a religious cult headed by the mysterious Jesus reborn ‘The Counselor’, who wandered around Brazil preaching the good word and collecting outcasts, misfits and hardened criminals and making them a part of his family/cult. This doesn’t sit well with the Brazilian government or the big cheese the land was stolen from so the army is dispatched to reclaim the land. What follows is a bloody, violent war. <br /><br />I’m an atheist but I have always been interested in religious sects and how manipulative they can be toward the weak and gullible. The Counselor is pretty much the 1800’s equivalent of David Koresh, who somehow takes on the role of the Chosen One only to be pursued and attacked by the authorities. Yes, his intentions were for the greater good and he brought acceptance and hope to many damaged people but you can’t just steal land that belongs elsewhere and expect to get away with it. <br /><br />This is an utterly fascinating but very involved book. At the end of my first couple of reading sessions I felt as if my progress was minimal but I eventually accepted that this wasn’t going to be an easy flowing, breeze through book; The War of the End of the World requires time and patience. Not only is this a history lesson into how utterly fascinating the past can be, it’s also a great story. It’s well written with superb character development and beautiful passages of prose. I couldn’t stretch to 5/5 as it does over stay its welcome by about fifty pages. That one small flaw aside The War of the End of the World is a masterpiece.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16629884823280628961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


