<div id="review_1347886621" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1347886621" />
    <a title="Bryan Murphy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10860999-bryan-murphy"><img alt="Bryan Murphy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442635328p2/10860999.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1347886621?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan Murphy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan Murphy" href="/user/show/10860999-bryan-murphy">Bryan Murphy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1347886621" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5609409722051586583">This novel reminds me forcefully of Conor Cruise O&apos;Brien&apos;s play &quot;Murderous Angels&quot; about men in thrall to conflicting ideals that lead them to disaster. O&apos;Brien&apos;s play was written in the 1960s and set in the 1960s. Vargas Llosa wrote his novel at the turn of the millennium but set it in the 1890s. The ideals that O’Brien focused on (the &quot;Murderous Angels&quot; in people’s heads) thus seem more contemporary: freedom and peace, whereas Vargas Llosa sets religious fundamentalism against nationalism, ide</span>
  <span id="freeText5609409722051586583" style="display:none">This novel reminds me forcefully of Conor Cruise O'Brien's play "Murderous Angels" about men in thrall to conflicting ideals that lead them to disaster. O'Brien's play was written in the 1960s and set in the 1960s. Vargas Llosa wrote his novel at the turn of the millennium but set it in the 1890s. The ideals that O’Brien focused on (the "Murderous Angels" in people’s heads) thus seem more contemporary: freedom and peace, whereas Vargas Llosa sets religious fundamentalism against nationalism, ideals which might seem less likely in our supposedly rational days to set people murdering each other and destroying their own lives, were they not already doing so in the Middle East and no doubt heading our way. Vargas Llosa’s great achievement here is to present events from the points of view of individuals with a range of irreconcilable beliefs and attitudes, and to do so without condescension or sentimentality, so that the reader can feel compassion for the characters, if not quite empathy. The author is a gifted story-teller, but is perhaps too wrapped up in that talent, for he drags the story on too long, so that by the time are supposed to feel the most compassion, compassion fatigue has begun to set in.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5609409722051586583" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

