<div id="review_1098437" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1098437" />
    <a title="Xio" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4825-xio"><img alt="Xio" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1364581623p2/4825.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1098437?book_show_action=true">May 08, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Xio" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Xio" href="/user/show/4825-xio">Xio</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4825-xio?shelf=unfinished">unfinished</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1098437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7552203009869559472">This is a book I ought to have picked up way back when I was a teen-ager and could stomach these excessively long-winded South American novels. Don&apos;t get me wrong...I found the book sort of fascinating until about the last 150 pages. And then I realized it was just going to go on in the same circles until it ran out of steam. And then, folks, I skipped to the final five pages and read those. The last paragraph is worth it. Those 145 pages I skipped, I find it difficult to believe I&apos;ve missed any</span>
  <span id="freeText7552203009869559472" style="display:none">This is a book I ought to have picked up way back when I was a teen-ager and could stomach these excessively long-winded South American novels. Don't get me wrong...I found the book sort of fascinating until about the last 150 pages. And then I realized it was just going to go on in the same circles until it ran out of steam. And then, folks, I skipped to the final five pages and read those. The last paragraph is worth it. Those 145 pages I skipped, I find it difficult to believe I've missed anything substantial. (I did skim them, rapidly)<br /><br />Ok. Turn of the century Brazil. The major players are the Republicans (divided into a militaristic and a parliamentarian grouping), the Monarchists (landowners) and an Anarchist-type on the run (aren't they always) who finds a certain (somewhat deluded) affinity with a group of religious folk who have decided (or who have chosen to accept as doctrine from one charismatic leader) to fight the Republic and all of its godless ways while at the same time living out very practically the idealist communal style the Anarchist has been fighting for.<br /><br />And they all fight each other in a series of battles. There are the usual intrigues of war, rapes, political philosophies being bantered about, starving conscripted soldiers and glorified religious figures...<br /><br />I did enjoy it, mostly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7552203009869559472" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


